Ah, the [Renaissance](/Renaissance). Humanity's rather self-congratulatory label for a few centuries where they decided to look backward to move forward. One might almost call it quaint, if it weren't so endlessly debated.

This particular discourse centers on the European [Renaissance](/Renaissance) of the 15th and 16th centuries. For those who insist on tracing these threads further back into the tapestry of human forgetfulness and rediscovery, there's the [Renaissance of the 12th century](/Renaissance_of_the_12th_century). And for those whose grasp of history is, shall we say, *fluid*, remember, this is not to be confused with [Reconnaissance](/Reconnaissance)—unless, of course, you're implying a period of intense intellectual scouting, which, for once, wouldn't be entirely wrong. For all other misinterpretations, consult the [Renaissance (disambiguation)](/Renaissance_(disambiguation)) page; there are many.

