### History and study

The study of the [Renaissance](/Renaissance) itself has, rather meta-textually, become a field of its own, rife with its own discoveries and endless re-evaluations:

*   [Age of Discovery](/Age_of_Discovery)
*   [Continuity thesis](/Continuity_thesis)
*   [High Renaissance](/High_Renaissance)

The [Renaissance](/Renaissance) ([UK](/British_English): [/rɪˈneɪsəns/](/Help:IPA/English) rin-AY-sənss , [US](/American_English): [/ˈrɛnəsɑːns/](/Help:IPA/English)&#32; [ⓘ](/File:En-us-Renaissance.ogg) REN-ə-sahnss ) &#91;1&#93; &#91;2&#93; &#91;a&#93; is not merely a pretty word borrowed from the French, but a designated [period of history](/Periodization) and a significant European [cultural movement](/Cultural_movement) predominantly spanning the 15th and 16th centuries. &#91; [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) &#93; Yes, the foundation for this assertion is apparently still being sought, which is entirely fitting for a period so defined by intellectual upheaval. It's conventionally understood as the pivotal juncture marking the transition from the often-maligned [Middle Ages](/Middle_Ages) to the dawn of what we now call [modernity](/Modernity). This era was largely characterized by a conscious, almost desperate, effort to not just revive, but to genuinely surpass the intellectual and artistic achievements of [classical antiquity](/Classical_antiquity). &#91; [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) &#93; One would think such a monumental shift would be universally acknowledged, but I suppose clarity is too much to ask.

This period, undeniably associated with profound [social change](/Social_change) across nearly every conceivable field and discipline—including the burgeoning realms of [art](/Renaissance_art) and [architecture](/Renaissance_architecture), the ever-shifting sands of politics, the flourishing of [literature](/Renaissance_literature), ambitious [exploration](/Renaissance_exploration) across uncharted waters, and foundational developments in [science](/Science_in_the_Renaissance)—found its initial, vibrant epicenter in the bustling [Republic of Florence](/Republic_of_Florence). From there, like a particularly virulent idea, it disseminated rapidly across the [rest of Italy](/Italian_Renaissance) before eventually permeating the intellectual and cultural landscape of Europe. The term *rinascita* ("rebirth"), a rather poetic and perhaps overly optimistic descriptor, first surfaced in the seminal work *[Lives of the Artists](/Lives_of_the_Artists)* (c. &#8201;1550) by the always-opinionated [Giorgio Vasari](/Giorgio_Vasari). It took a few more centuries, predictably, for the rest of Europe to catch up, with the French word *renaissance* being formally adopted into English as the defining term for this period during the 1830s. &#91;4&#93; &#91;b&#93; Humanity's timeline for grasping significant shifts has always been rather